.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A442%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews.sky.com%2Fstory%2Fparasite-actor-lee-sun-kyun-found-dead-in-apparent-suicide-13038095%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews-sky-com.cdn.ampproject.org%2Fc%2Fs%2Fnews.sky.com%2Fstory%2Famp%2Fparasite-actor-lee-sun-kyun-found-dead-in-apparent-suicide-13038095%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews.sky.com%2Fstory%2Famp%2Fparasite-actor-lee-sun-kyun-found-dead-in-apparent-suicide-13038095%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Reminiscences%20of%20Father%2C%20Mother%20and%20Me%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cimg%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26152758%2FDSC_1008-1.jpg%5C%22%3E%3Cp%3EIt%20is%20the%20month%20of%20December%2C%20the%20last%20month%20of%20the%20year%2C%20the%20last%20month%20of%20Father%E2%80%99s%20life%20in%20its%20earthly%20form.%20I%20find%20myself%20thinking%20about%20him%20evermore.%20I%20am%20reading%20the%20final%20proofs%20of%20my%20Ghalib%20book%20%E2%80%93%20it%20is%20my%20commentary%20on%2030%20%E2%80%9Crejected%E2%80%9D%20ghazals.%20By%20some%20strange%20coincidence%20I%20was%20reading%20the%20final%20proofs%20of%20my%20first%20Ghalib%20book%20in%20the%20December%20of%202020.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMy%20Father%2C%20Shamsur%20Rahman%20Faruqi%2C%20was%20one%20of%2013%20siblings.%20He%20was%20the%20first%20male%20born%20after%20two%20older%20sisters.%20He%20married%20my%20mother%20against%20the%20wishes%20of%20his%20parents%20when%20he%20was%20barely%2021.%20She%20was%2026%20and%20the%20principal%20of%20a%20girl%E2%80%99s%20school.%20I%20was%20their%20first%20born.%20Father%2C%20after%20some%20stints%20as%20an%20English%20lecturer%20in%20provincial%20colleges%2C%20had%20joined%20the%20administrative%20services.%20At%20first%2C%20he%20was%20posted%20in%20faraway%20places%20like%20Shillong%20in%20Assam%20and%20Nagpur%20in%20Maharashtra.%20Mother%20never%20left%20her%20job.%20His%20letters%20to%20my%20mother%20were%20filled%20with%20angst.%20Mother%20and%20I%20lived%20with%20her%20parents.%20She%20was%20the%20eldest%20in%20the%20family.%20I%20was%20adored%20by%20my%20grandparents%2C%20aunts%20and%20uncles.%20My%20parents%20coped%20with%20their%20loneliness%20in%20different%20ways.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EI%20remember%20Mother%20being%20wrapped%20up%20in%20her%20work%2C%20a%20rather%20distant%20being%2C%20impatient%20and%20short%20tempered.%20Father%20in%20his%20letters%20implored%20her%20to%20be%20kinder%20and%20more%20patient%20with%20me.%20Looking%20back%20at%20those%20childhood%20years%20etched%20in%20my%20memory%2C%20I%20can%20now%20understand%20her%20preoccupations%20and%20frustrations.%20My%20first%20concrete%20memories%20of%20Father%20are%20from%20the%20times%20he%20was%20posted%20in%20Delhi%20as%20the%20Superintendent%20of%20Post%20Offices.%20I%20had%20not%20started%20school%20yet.%20Here%2C%20I%20would%20like%20to%20share%20an%20incident%20from%20that%20time%20that%20was%20narrated%20often%20in%20our%20family%20get%20togethers.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFather%20had%20a%20second-hand%20car%20%E2%80%93%20a%20black%20%E2%80%9CHindustan%E2%80%9D.%20Its%20ignition%20often%20failed%20and%20need%20cranking%20with%20a%20hand%20tool.%20But%20that%20is%20not%20the%20point%20of%20my%20story.%20My%20story%20is%20about%20my%20little%20purse%20in%20which%20I%20kept%20an%20assortment%20of%20things%20that%20caught%20my%20fancy%20%E2%80%93%20like%20shells%20gathered%20from%20sand%20pits%20and%20other%20sparkly%20things.%20In%20this%20little%20purse%20I%20put%20the%20keys%20to%20the%20Hindustan.%20Summer%20was%20over%20and%20we%20were%20returning%20to%20Allahabad%3B%20Father%20was%20going%20to%20drive%20Mother%20and%20me%20to%20the%20railway%20station.%20He%20began%20searching%20for%20the%20car%20keys%20but%20they%20were%20nowhere%20to%20be%20found.%20Eventually%2C%20he%20called%20a%20taxi%20that%20took%20us%20to%20the%20railway%20station.%20I%20sat%20demurely%20in%20the%20compartment.%20After%20the%20train%20had%20gathered%20speed%2C%20I%20opened%20my%20box%20of%20treasures.%20I%20unclasped%20my%20little%20purse%20from%20which%20I%20triumphantly%20pulled%20out%20the%20car%20keys.%20I%20have%20no%20recollection%20of%20this%20incident%20or%20what%20might%20have%20happened%20after%20I%20brandished%20the%20keys.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20434px)%2085vw%2C%20434px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26144042%2FIMG_5177.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22434%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26144042%2FIMG_5177.jpg%20552w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26144042%2FIMG_5177-259x300.jpg%20259w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-690755%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22503%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EMy%20parents%20with%20my%20little%20sister.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20Railways%20had%20first%2C%20second%2C%20and%2C%20third%20class%20compartments.%20We%20traveled%20second%20class.%20I%20remember%20the%20olive%20green%20not-too-thick%20upholstery%20that%20covered%20the%20wooden%20sleepers%20of%20the%20second%20class.%20It%20was%20embossed%20with%20the%20northern%20railway%E2%80%99s%20logo.%20I%20can%20recall%20those%20rail%20commutes%20accompanying%20Mother%20when%20she%20travelled%20to%20spend%20vacation%20days%20with%20Father.%20The%20journeys%20were%20long.%20I%20would%20invariably%20sit%20by%20the%20window%2C%20taking%20in%20the%20changing%20pastoral%20scenery.%20In%20his%20last%20days%20Father%20recalled%20Mother%E2%80%99s%20courage%20to%20travel%20all%20those%20distances.%20She%20was%20young%20and%20beautiful%2C%20he%20said%2C%20and%20it%20took%20a%20lot%20of%20guts%20to%20travel%20alone%20with%20a%20small%20child.%20Mother%20had%20lots%20of%20guts.%20I%20caught%20a%20glimpse%20of%20the%20sweet%2C%20romantic%20side%20of%20my%20parent%E2%80%99s%20relationship%20when%20Father%20shared%20this%20perspective%20of%20the%20journey%20with%20me.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFinally%2C%20a%20time%20came%20when%20Father%20was%20posted%20at%20Allahabad%20and%20my%20parents%20could%20live%20together.%20They%20rented%20a%20bungalow%20in%20the%20Civil%20Lines%20area.%20The%20house%20itself%20was%20quite%20small%20but%20it%20had%20vast%20lawns%20and%20an%20equally%20extensive%20backyard%20populated%20with%20guava%20and%20mango%20trees%2C%20a%20cluster%20of%20big%20banana%20trees%20that%20produced%20special%20small%20size%20%E2%80%9C%3Cem%3Echiniya%20kela%3C%2Fem%3E%E2%80%9D%20and%20a%20massive%20%3Cem%3Ebel%3C%2Fem%3E%20tree.%20The%20backyard%20was%20fenced%20off%20with%20a%20row%20of%20thorny%20%3Cem%3Ejangal%20jalebi%3C%2Fem%3E%20bushes.%20A%20great%20leafy%20neem%20tree%20spread%20its%20sturdy%20branches%20to%20shade%20the%20driveway.%20This%20is%20where%20my%20parents%20parked%20their%20cars.%20Father%20had%20a%20Fiat%20and%20Mother%20drove%20a%20red%2C%20two%20door%20Standard%20Herald.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cins%3EAlso%20read%3A%20%3Ca%20title%3D%5C%22Farewell%20Shamsur%20Rahman%20Faruqi%3A%20The%20Sun%20That%20Set%20in%20the%20Earth%C2%A0%C2%A0%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fbooks%2Fshamsur-rahman-faruqi-urdu-literature-obituary%5C%22%3EFarewell%20Shamsur%20Rahman%20Faruqi%3A%20The%20Sun%20That%20Set%20in%20the%20Earth%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fins%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EI%20was%20fortunate%20to%20grow%20up%20not%20in%20an%20urban%20jungle%20but%20a%20neighbourhood%20encircled%20with%20nature%E2%80%99s%20beauty.%20My%20parents%20took%20a%20lot%20of%20interest%20in%20plants%2C%20they%20loved%20animals.%20There%20was%20an%20array%20of%20pots%20of%20cacti%20on%20the%20front%20verandah.%20One%20day%20Father%20and%20I%20excitedly%20admired%20the%20ruby%20red%20flower%20that%20emerged%20from%20a%20thorny%20cactus.%20I%20always%20wanted%20to%20be%20the%20first%20to%20spot%20a%20new%20blossom%20and%20report%20to%20Father.%20In%20this%20way%20I%20developed%20an%20affinity%20with%20cacti%2C%20a%20fascination%20with%20thorns.%20The%20moments%20we%20exulted%20over%20the%20exquisite%20blooms%20are%20still%20fresh%20in%20my%20memory.%20Here%20I%20must%20mention%20the%20vine%20with%20feathery%2C%20needle%20like%20leaves%20on%20thorny%2C%20woody%2C%20twisty%20stems%20that%20wound%20around%20the%20verandah%20pillars.%20It%20bore%20minuscule%20flowers%20growing%20on%20fern-like%20extensions.%20The%20flowers%20were%20pale%20but%20exuded%20a%20honey%20fragrance%20which%20attracted%20lots%20of%20bees.%20Father%20mentioned%20that%20this%20vine%20was%20called%20%E2%80%9C%3Cem%3Eishq-e%20pecha%C3%B1%3C%2Fem%3E%E2%80%9D.%20The%20poetic%20name%20intrigued%20me.%20Certainly%2C%20the%20vine%20was%20thorny%20and%20intricate%2C%20but%20why%20would%20%3Cem%3Eishq%3C%2Fem%3E%20be%20thorny%3F%20I%20was%20only%20eight%20years%20old.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20439px)%2085vw%2C%20439px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26151407%2F6f21a264-0e72-4ca9-8565-f943908068e2.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22439%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26151407%2F6f21a264-0e72-4ca9-8565-f943908068e2.jpg%20720w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26151407%2F6f21a264-0e72-4ca9-8565-f943908068e2-263x300.jpg%20263w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-690756%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22501%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EMe%20and%20Ammi.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFlowering%20bushes%2C%20vines%20and%20trees%20have%20such%20beautiful%20names.%20I%20owe%20it%20to%20Father%20for%20introducing%20me%20to%20the%20magic%20of%20names%20%E2%80%93%20Juhi%2C%20Chandni%2C%20Kamini%2C%20Madhu-Malti%2C%20Amar%20Bel%2C%20Gul-e%20Chin%2C%20Gul%20Mohar%3B%20I%20carry%20their%20distinct%20flower-fragrances%20inside%20my%20nostrils%2C%20their%20velvet%20textures%20on%20my%20fingertips.%20In%20the%20rainy%20season%2C%20the%20month%20of%20S%C4%81van%2C%20a%20swing%20would%20be%20strung%20from%20the%20neem%20tree.%20One%20could%20only%20swing%20when%20the%20cars%20were%20not%20parked%20under%20the%20tree%2C%20or%20were%20parked%20at%20a%20safe%20distance.%20One%20morning%2C%20I%20was%20impatient%20and%20couldn%E2%80%99t%20wait%20for%20the%20cars%20to%20be%20moved.%20I%20will%20swing%20gently%2C%20I%20thought.%20But%20I%20got%20carried%20away.%20The%20swing%E2%80%99s%20edge%20hit%20the%20Fiat%E2%80%99s%20headlight%20with%20an%20ominous%20crunch.%20The%20glass%20shattered%20but%20didn%E2%80%99t%20fall%20out%20because%20it%20was%20held%20by%20the%20steel%20frame.%20I%20crept%20back%20indoors%20and%20did%20not%20breathe%20a%20word%20about%20what%20had%20happened.%20It%20was%20a%20Sunday%20and%20the%20day%20unfolded%20leisurely.%20My%20parents%20had%20to%20go%20to%20a%20meeting%20in%20the%20afternoon.%20They%20took%20the%20car%20without%20noticing%20the%20shattered%20headlight.%20I%20breathed%20easier.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFather%20called%20me%20when%20they%20returned.%20%E2%80%9CWhy%20didn%E2%80%99t%20you%20tell%20us%20about%20the%20broken%20head%20lamp%3F%E2%80%9D%20he%20asked.%20%E2%80%9CThe%20glass%20and%20frame%20fell%20off%20in%20the%20middle%20of%20traffic%20and%20could%20have%20caused%20an%20accident.%E2%80%9D%20I%20stood%20there%20staring%20at%20my%20feet.%20The%20answer%20was%20that%20I%20was%20scared%20to%20tell%20them.%20Scared%20of%20what%3F%20Being%20severely%20reprimanded%3B%20of%20harsh%20words.%20If%20I%20was%20ever%20praised%20as%20a%20child%2C%20I%20don%E2%80%99t%20remember.%20My%20parents%20said%20harsh%20words%20and%20forgot%20about%20them%20later%2C%20but%20those%20words%20were%20unforgettable%20for%20me.%20Perhaps%20if%20I%20had%20confessed%20that%20I%20was%20desperately%20scared%20(of%20them)%20it%20would%20have%20helped.%20Our%20relationship%20was%20filled%20with%20misunderstandings.%20I%20became%20secretive.%20I%20felt%20unloved%20and%20unappreciated.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAfter%20six%20years%20in%20Allahabad%2C%20Father%20was%20posted%20at%20Lucknow.%20Second%20Saturdays%20of%20every%20month%20were%20special%20because%20he%20drove%20down%20for%20the%20weekend.%20His%20visits%20were%20precious%20and%20time%20flew.%20Occasionally%2C%20I%20had%20school%20holidays%20like%20the%20long%20break%20around%20Christmas%20and%20could%20drive%20back%20with%20him%20to%20Lucknow.%20The%20winter%20days%20spent%20with%20Father%20without%20my%20mother%20and%20sister%20were%20exclusive%20and%20distinct.%20This%20was%20the%20time%20when%20my%20literary%20tastes%20were%20nourished.%20Father%20would%20drop%20me%20off%20at%20the%20British%20Council%20Library%20in%20Hazrat%20Ganj%20on%20his%20way%20to%20office.%20I%20would%20join%20him%20for%20lunch%2C%20his%20little%20girl%20with%20a%20bunch%20of%20his%20fellow%20officers.%20Post%20lunch%20I%20would%20sit%20in%20his%20office%20and%20work%20on%20writing%20stories.%20I%20felt%20very%20important.%20On%20the%20way%20home%20we%20would%20talk%20about%20what%20I%20was%20reading%20and%20writing.%20It%20was%20bliss.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWe%20went%20to%20book%20shops.%20We%20browsed%20for%20hours.%20We%20returned%20with%20an%20armful%20of%20books.%20On%20weekends%20we%20would%20go%20to%20the%20old%20city%2C%20to%20Chowk%2C%20and%20Nakhas.%20Here%20we%20checked%20out%20Urdu%20books.%20There%20were%20vendors%20on%20the%20side%20walk%20displaying%20old%2C%20rare%20books.%20The%20energy%20of%20the%20market%20was%20a%20world%20apart%20from%20the%20quiet%20Hazrat%20Ganj%20book%20shops.%20Then%20there%20was%20the%20bird%20market%20under%20a%20sprawling%20banyan%20tree%20in%20Nakhas.%20Parrots%2C%20finches%2C%20pigeons%2C%20mynahs%2C%20budgerigars%20of%20all%20colours%20chirped%20here.%20Their%20songs%20intermingled%20with%20the%20raucous%20voices%20of%20sellers%20and%20buyers%20bargaining.%20Father%20loved%20all%20creatures%20but%20it%20was%20practical%20for%20him%20to%20have%20some%20pet%20birds.%20In%20Lucknow%20he%20kept%20a%20two-tier%20airy%20cage%20with%20an%20assortment%20of%20%3Cem%3Elal%20muniyas%3C%2Fem%3E%20(red%20finches)%20and%20other%20local%20finches.%20Pigeon%20fanciers%20were%20a%20part%20of%20Lucknow%20culture%20and%20the%20variety%20of%20pigeons%20at%20the%20market%20was%20extraordinary.%20Father%20couldn%E2%80%99t%20resist%20getting%20a%20pair%20of%20pigeons.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cins%3EAlso%20read%3A%20%3Ca%20title%3D%5C%22Shamsur%20Rahman%20Faruqi%3A%20The%20Ustad%20Who%20Could%20Catch%20the%20Bustle%20in%20A%20Flower%E2%80%99s%20Scent%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fthe-arts%2Fshamsur-rahman-faruqi-tribute-geeta-patel%5C%22%3EShamsur%20Rahman%20Faruqi%3A%20The%20Ustad%20Who%20Could%20Catch%20the%20Bustle%20in%20A%20Flower%E2%80%99s%20Scent%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fins%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESummer%20months%20we%20spent%20together%20as%20a%20family.%20Lucknow%20had%20a%20lot%20to%20offer%3B%20we%20liked%20being%20there.%20But%20home%20was%20always%20Allahabad.%20As%20I%20grew%20older%2C%20my%20relationship%20with%20my%20parents%20continued%20to%20be%20angst%20filled.%20Father%20understood%20my%20rebellious%20streak.%20Mother%20seemed%20oblivious%20to%20the%20emotions%20bottled%20up%20inside%20me.%20I%20was%20proud%20of%20my%20mother%E2%80%99s%20stature%20but%20I%20envied%20peers%20whose%20mothers%20were%20not%20busy%20professionals%20and%20fussed%20over%20their%20meals%20and%20homework.%20I%20was%20overly%20sensitive.%20I%20cried%20a%20lot.%20I%20sulked.%20I%20was%20angry.%20My%20remarkable%20exposure%20to%20the%20world%20of%20poetry%2C%20particularly%20of%20the%20ghazal%2C%20kindled%20raw%20emotions.%20It%20was%20a%20difficult%20time%20and%20I%20am%20glad%20it%20is%20over.%20For%20years%20I%20struggled%20to%20find%20a%20path%20that%20would%20suit%20my%20peculiar%20combination%20of%20erudition%20and%20emotion.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EI%20followed%20different%20paths%20only%20to%20return%20to%20my%20base.%20The%20parental%20home%2C%20a%20storm%20filled%20haven.%20Mother%2C%20still%20alone%2C%20welcomed%20me%20and%20was%20a%20pillar%20of%20support.%20A%20new%20bond%20between%20us%20flowered.%20She%20doted%20on%20my%20children.%20She%20encouraged%20me%20in%20every%20way.%20My%20Mother%20was%20an%20educationist.%20A%20pioneer%20in%20educating%20the%20poor%2C%20underprivileged%20girls.%20Her%20school%20in%20the%20outskirts%20of%20Allahabad%20was%20inaugurated%20in%201956.%20The%20area%20was%20a%20settlement%20area%20for%20refugees%20from%20Pakistan.%20A%20Sufi%20khanqah%20nearby%20gave%20shelter%20to%20the%20homeless%20poor.%20An%20overbridge%20to%20bypass%20a%20busy%20railway%20crossing%20became%20another%20refuge%20for%20homeless%20people.%20Mother%20would%20stop%20by%20these%20places%20and%20encourage%20parents%20to%20send%20the%20children%20to%20school.%20I%20began%20to%20take%20interest%20in%20the%20school.%20Thus%20began%20a%20wonderful%20rapport%20with%20my%20mother.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMy%20stars%20were%20changing%2C%20though.%20An%20unexpected%20opportunity%20to%20teach%20at%20the%20University%20of%20Pennsylvania%20came%20my%20way.%20It%20was%20bittersweet.%20A%20chance%20that%20might%20open%20a%20door%20to%20another%20world.%20Mother%20was%20sad%20to%20let%20me%20go%20but%20she%20didn%E2%80%99t%20object.%20There%20were%20farewells%2C%20hugs%2C%20tears%3B%20I%20left%20the%20children%20in%20her%20care%20and%20went%20to%20Philadelphia%20%E2%80%93%20alone.%20I%20was%20alone%20for%20the%20first%20time%20in%20my%20life.%20Those%20early%20months%20were%20pitiless.%20My%20furnished%20apartment%20on%20the%2015th%20floor%20had%20basic%20furniture.%20The%20kitchen%20was%20bare.%20The%20shelves%20and%20drawers%20were%20empty.%20I%20had%20brought%20a%20pressure%20cooker%20with%20me%20and%20that%20was%20the%20only%20thing%20I%20had%20so%20I%20filled%20it%20up%20with%20water%20because%20I%20was%20thirsty.%20It%20felt%20strange%20drinking%20water%20straight%20from%20the%20tap.%20I%20had%20never%20ridden%20on%20a%20subway.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20296px)%2085vw%2C%20296px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26143328%2Funnamed.jpeg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22296%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26143328%2Funnamed.jpeg%20296w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26143328%2Funnamed-225x300.jpeg%20225w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-690752%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22394%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EFather%20during%20his%202014%20visit%20to%20Charlottesville.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EI%20have%20been%20living%20in%20the%20US%20for%2025%20years.%20I%20am%20holding%20on%20to%20my%20Indian%20passport%20and%20managing%20with%20a%20Green%20Card.%20Something%20deep%20inside%20told%20me%20to%20keep%20that%20legal%20marker%20of%20my%20identity.%20I%20returned%20%E2%80%9Chome%E2%80%9D%20every%20year.%20I%20had%20no%20problems%20falling%20into%20the%20rhythm%20of%20life%20in%20India.%20Change%20is%20inevitable%2C%20inexorable%3B%20it%20happens%20slowly%2C%20it%20can%20happen%20in%20an%20instant.%20The%20pandemic%20changed%20our%20lives%20dramatically.%20The%20first%20phase%20unfolded%20with%20the%20horror%20of%20contagion%20stalking%20us.%20A%20new%20vocabulary%20of%20social%20distancing%20began%20circulating.%20Then%20there%20was%20the%20fear%20of%20isolation%2C%20the%20ache%20of%20loneliness%2C%20the%20frustration%20of%20helplessness%20as%20we%20watched%20Covid%20strike%20loved%20ones.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWe%20hoped%20for%20a%20vaccine%20by%20the%20year%E2%80%99s%20end.%20In%20November%2C%20my%20sister%20reported%20that%20Father%20was%20ill%3B%20it%20was%20Covid-19.%20Only%20my%20Indian%20passport%20could%20get%20me%20back%20to%20home.%20I%20took%20the%20Air%20India%20flight%20directly%20to%20Delhi.%20Father%20was%20in%20hospital%20in%20the%20Covid%20section.%20The%20Covid%20wards%20of%20even%20the%20elitist%20hospitals%20in%20New%20Delhi%20were%20nightmares.%20Writing%20about%20those%20days%20and%20nights%20after%20three%20years%20have%20passed%20still%20gives%20me%20goosebumps.%20The%20treatments%20for%20Covid%20were%20in%20an%20experimental%20stage.%20Doctors%20took%20chances%2C%20concoctions%20and%20cocktails%20of%20drugs%20were%20tried.%20They%20mostly%20failed%20but%20occasionally%20succeeded.%20Father%20received%20plasma%20therapy%3B%20he%20was%20on%20a%20powerful%20string%20of%20steroids.%20The%20steroids%20destroyed%20whatever%20immune%20system%20he%20had.%20He%20was%20losing%20strength%20every%20day.%20He%20wanted%20out.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWe%20had%20to%20get%20Father%20out%20of%20the%20hospital.%20We%20didn%E2%80%99t%20want%20him%20to%20spend%20his%20days%20and%20nights%20in%20isolation%20at%20the%20mercy%20of%20hospital%20staff.%20After%20a%20lot%20of%20persistence%2C%20we%20succeeded%20in%20getting%20him%20discharged.%20The%20evening%20we%20got%20him%20to%20my%20sister%E2%80%99s%20apartment%20in%20South%20Delhi%20was%20one%20of%20jubilation.%20My%20sister%20had%20done%20the%20utmost%20to%20secure%20private%20nursing%20staff.%20Her%20daughter%20had%20scoured%20Delhi%20and%20arranged%20for%20hospital%20grade%20equipment%20for%20a%20critical%20patient%2C%20from%20oxygen%20concentrators%20to%20spare%20cylinders.%20It%20was%20the%20last%20week%20of%20November%3B%20Delhi%20was%20unusually%20cold%20with%20grey%20skies%2C%20icy%20winds%20and%20a%20high%20pollution%20index.%20We%20all%20had%20had%20Covid%20in%20different%20intensities%20of%20virus%20load.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWith%20Father%20home%2C%20we%20were%20all%20in%20high%20spirits.%20He%20joined%20us%20in%20singing%20old%20film%20songs%20from%20the%201950s.%20We%20drank%20tea.%20I%20noticed%20that%20his%20one%20eye%20was%20badly%20swollen.%20The%20nurse%20made%20a%20temporary%20patch%20to%20shield%20it.%20The%20next%20morning%20it%20was%20worse.%20It%20didn%E2%80%99t%20get%20better.%20Yet%2C%20those%20days%20and%20nights%20were%20the%20most%20exquisite%20experience%20of%20love%20and%20pain.%20My%20job%20was%20to%20bring%20the%20tray%20of%20morning%20tea%20and%20biscuits.%20I%20would%20coax%20Father%20to%20eat%20rusks%20soaked%20in%20tea%2C%20regale%20him%20with%20stories%20of%20pets%2C%20flowers%20that%20were%20blooming%20now%20and%20had%20bloomed%20in%20the%20past%2C%20recite%20favourite%20ghazal%20verses.%20I%20would%20manage%20to%20get%20through%20four%20rusks%20before%20he%20would%20protest.%20He%20loved%20fine%20tea%3B%20the%20best%20of%20Darjeeling%2C%20Oolong%2C%20Temi%2C%20Jasmine%2C%20occasionally%20Earl%20Grey.%20The%20cup%20had%20to%20be%20elegant%2C%20made%20of%20bone%20china%2C%20of%20the%20right%20shape%20and%20size.%20Spoons%20had%20to%20be%20specific%20for%20stirring%20tea.%20He%20had%20an%20aversion%20to%20ugly%20spoons.%20Any%20time%20could%20be%20tea%20time%2C%20but%20morning%20and%20afternoon%20teas%20were%20special.%20He%20seldom%20poured%20his%20own%20tea%3B%20Mother%20would%20do%20that.%20But%20she%20had%20left%20us%20in%202007.%20After%20her%20passing%2C%20it%20was%20a%20void%20that%20no%20one%20could%20possibly%20fill.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMy%20sister%20and%20I%20poured%20tea%20when%20we%20were%20visiting%20and%20he%20loved%20that.%20He%20drank%20it%20tepid%20but%20it%20had%20to%20be%20hot%20when%20poured.%20Conversations%20over%20morning%20tea%20ranged%20over%20many%20subjects%3B%20from%20the%20weather%20to%20his%20beloved%20pets%2C%20from%20his%20work%20to%20mundane%20anxieties.%20Generous%20to%20a%20fault%2C%20he%20felt%20short%20of%20money%20to%20give%20away%20to%20the%20charities%20he%20supported.%20The%20local%20graveyard%20was%20one%20such%20project%20that%20he%20took%20on%20with%20dedication.%20The%20cemetery%20was%20in%20shambles.%20Encroachments%20had%20reduced%20the%20area%20to%20a%20third%20of%20its%20original%20size.%20There%20was%20no%20boundary%20wall%3B%20goats%20and%20pigs%20and%20stray%20dogs%20roamed.%20It%20became%20the%20space%20for%20%3Cem%3Edhobis%3C%2Fem%3E%20to%20dry%20laundry.%20Among%20other%20things%2C%20it%20was%20an%20open-air%20latrine.%20A%20committee%20was%20formed%3B%20the%20graveyard%20was%20cleaned%20up.%20Most%20of%20the%20committee%20members%20lie%20buried%20there%20now.%20My%20parent%E2%80%99s%20graves%20are%20side%20by%20side.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20448px)%2085vw%2C%20448px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26143910%2FIMG_3111.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22448%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26143910%2FIMG_3111.jpg%20566w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26143910%2FIMG_3111-265x300.jpg%20265w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-690753%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22507%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EFather%20with%20his%20beloved%20dogs.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20conversations%20I%20had%20with%20Father%20in%20the%20post%20Covid%20days%20were%20wistful.%20He%20remembered%20incidents%20from%20his%20childhood%20and%20mine.%20I%20listened%3B%20he%20talked%20in%20English%20when%20the%20recollection%20was%20sad.%20%E2%80%9COnce%20when%20I%20was%20small%2C%20I%20met%20a%20gentleman%20who%20knew%20exactly%20what%20I%20was%20thinking.%E2%80%9D%20Thus%20began%20one%20poignant%20story.%20%E2%80%9CIt%20was%20a%20very%20hot%20summer%3B%20I%20must%20have%20been%20eight%20years%20old.%20I%20was%20walking%20home%20trying%20to%20stay%20in%20the%20shade.%20I%20longed%20for%20a%20big%2C%20cool%20slice%20of%20melon.%20I%20loved%20melons%20but%20my%20mother%20rationed%20the%20fruit%20strictly%20among%20us%20and%20I%20silently%20craved%20for%20more.%20That%20day%2C%20I%20was%20extremely%20dejected%20as%20I%20slowly%20walked%20by%20the%20edge%20of%20the%20road%20in%20the%20shade%20of%20the%20masjid.%20Suddenly%20I%20saw%20a%20man%2C%20a%20stranger%20coming%20towards%20me.%20He%20stopped%20as%20he%20drew%20closer.%20%E2%80%98You%20want%20a%20slice%20of%20melon%2C%20don%E2%80%99t%20you%3F%E2%80%99%20the%20stranger%20said.%20He%20looked%20at%20me%20with%20kindness.%20Tears%20rolled%20from%20my%20eyes.%20How%20did%20the%20stranger%20know%20my%20thoughts%3F%20I%20never%20saw%20the%20stranger%20again.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EI%20absorbed%20this%20story.%20Another%20touching%20story%20(which%20I%20have%20shared%20in%20another%20reminiscence)%20was%20about%20puppies.%20He%20rescued%20two%20puppies%20and%20carried%20them%20home%20in%20his%20pocket.%20%E2%80%9CThey%20were%20small-small%20puppies%2C%E2%80%9D%20Father%20said.%20But%20he%20wasn%E2%80%99t%20allowed%20to%20keep%20them.%20%E2%80%9CTheir%20mouths%20are%20dirty%2C%E2%80%9D%20his%20father%20said.%20He%20took%20them%20back%20to%20their%20mother%20crying%20all%20the%20way.%20I%20loved%20the%20way%20Father%20used%20%E2%80%9Csmall%E2%80%9D%20in%20conversation.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cins%3EAlso%20read%3A%20%3Ca%20title%3D%5C%22On%20Returning%20Home%20to%20Father%E2%80%99s%20Library%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fculture%2Fshamsur-rahman-faruqi-library%5C%22%3EOn%20Returning%20Home%20to%20Father%E2%80%99s%20Library%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fins%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHe%20missed%20the%20Allahabad%20home.%20He%20would%20talk%20about%20the%20times%20when%20%E2%80%9Cyour%20mother%20and%20I%20were%20saving%20every%20penny%20to%20build%20it.%E2%80%9D%20He%20didn%E2%80%99t%20address%20Mother%20by%20her%20name%3B%20she%20called%20him%20%E2%80%9CFaruqi%20sahib.%E2%80%9D%20We%20had%20to%20get%20Father%20home%20before%20it%20got%20too%20late.%20First%2C%20we%20thought%20of%20journeying%20by%20train%20as%20he%20could%20certainly%20not%20travel%20on%20a%20regular%20flight.%20Precious%20time%20ticked%20by%3B%20the%20train%20idea%20had%20to%20be%20dropped.%20We%20became%20desperate%3B%20we%20could%20charter%20a%20medical%20plane.%20In%20moments%20of%20crisis%20our%20minds%20become%20numb.%20My%20sister%20signed%20up%20with%20a%20plane%20service%2C%20we%20got%20Father%20in%20a%20wheelchair%20and%20waited.%20Then%20at%20the%20last%20moment%20it%20was%20revealed%20that%20a%20Covid%20negative%20certificate%20was%20required%20to%20exit%20Delhi.%20Father%20sat%20patiently%20in%20the%20wheel%20chair%2C%20losing%20strength%20every%20minute.%20It%20was%20our%20last%20night%20in%20Delhi%20and%20the%20longest%20one.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EOur%20Yoga%20teacher%20had%20held%20us%20together%20in%20moments%20of%20panic.%20He%20came%20over%20to%20keep%20vigil.%20He%20was%20Father%E2%80%99s%20teacher%20too.%20Father%20spoke%20his%20last%20words%20to%20him.%20After%20that%20he%20only%20communicated%20with%20his%20eyes%20and%20hands.%20At%20dawn%20the%20van%20to%20take%20us%20to%20the%20airport%20arrived.%20It%20was%20supposed%20to%20be%20an%20ambulance%20but%20it%20was%20cold%20as%20an%20icebox%20and%20patchy.%20Apprehension%20of%20the%20coming%20journey%20filled%20me%20with%20dread%20but%20I%20was%20outwardly%20calm.%20There%20was%20room%20for%20only%20two%20passengers.%20Our%20cousin%20who%20had%20been%20with%20us%20throughout%20this%20time%20was%20accompanying%20me.%20The%20rest%20of%20the%20family%20was%20taking%20the%20early%20flight.%20Father%20spoke%20with%20his%20eyes.%20We%20made%20the%20journey%20in%20the%20little%20plane%20to%20Allahabad.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20370px)%2085vw%2C%20370px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26143946%2F00C51B34-99A8-42C4-A8DB-524A59EE22D1.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22370%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26143946%2F00C51B34-99A8-42C4-A8DB-524A59EE22D1.jpg%20466w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26143946%2F00C51B34-99A8-42C4-A8DB-524A59EE22D1-218x300.jpg%20218w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-690754%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22508%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EDecember%2022%2C%202019.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ENothing%20could%20be%20more%20beautiful%20than%20homecoming.%20The%20house%20was%20filled%20with%20relatives.%20Father%E2%80%99s%20two%20brothers%20were%20there.%20The%20emerald%20lawn%20glistened%20with%20dew%2C%20%3Cem%3Elahsunia%3C%2Fem%3E%20flowers%20cascaded%20over%20the%20terrace%2C%20finches%20chirped%20in%20the%3Cem%3E%20narangi%3C%2Fem%3E%20tree%20by%20the%20gate.%20Winters%20in%20Allahabad%20have%20a%20special%20charm%2C%20a%20heady%20mixture%20of%20the%20warmth%20in%20cold%20that%20exudes%20from%20the%20Sangam%20of%20the%20holy%20rivers.%20It%20was%20December%2025%2C%20Christmas%20day.%20With%20so%20many%20helping%20hands%20Father%20was%20easily%20carried%20to%20his%20bedroom%20and%20the%20large%20%3Cem%3Eshisham%3C%2Fem%3E%20wood%20beds%20that%20my%20parents%20had%20custom%20made%20from%20Bareilly%20half%20a%20century%20ago.%20He%20gazed%20at%20the%20loving%20faces%20surrounding%20him.%20He%20possibly%20missed%20his%20favourite%20dog%20Bholi%20who%20was%20locked%20in%20her%20kennel%20out%20of%20respect%20for%20visitors.%20Someone%20called%20%E2%80%93%20bring%20Bholi.%20But%20no%20one%20did.%20We%20were%20tracking%20the%20flight%20on%20which%20my%20sister%2C%20her%20daughters%20and%20the%20two%20nurses%20were%20due%20to%20arrive.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EA%20doctor%20came%20and%20suggested%20that%20Father%20should%20be%20put%20on%20a%20ventilator.%20Breakfast%20was%20on%20the%20table%20for%20us.%20Father%20was%20taking%20his%20last%20breaths.%20He%20had%20been%20saving%20precious%20breaths%20to%20get%20home.%20There%20was%20a%20smile%20on%20his%20face%2C%20the%20transition%20was%20peaceful.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWhy%20should%20I%20share%20my%20pain%20with%20my%20readers%3F%20And%2C%20who%20would%20want%20to%20read%20it%3F%20There%20is%20beauty%20in%20pain%2C%20that%20is%20what%20I%20had%20learned%20from%20reading%20classical%20ghazals%20with%20Father.%20He%20taught%20me%20to%20appreciate%20and%20enjoy%20the%20finest%20things%20that%20art%20and%20nature%20can%20offer%2C%20like%20Ghalib%E2%80%99s%20%E2%80%9Cautumn%20rose%E2%80%9D%2C%20%E2%80%9Clamp%20at%20dawn%E2%80%9D%20and%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20fairy%20in%20the%20mirror%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fauthor%2Fmehrafshanfarooqi%5C%22%3E%3Cspan%3EMehr%3C%2Fspan%3E%C2%A0Afshan%20Farooqi%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0is%20associate%20professor%20at%20the%20Department%20of%20Middle%20Eastern%20and%20South%20Asian%20Languages%20and%20Cultures%2C%20University%20of%20Virginia%2C%20US.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1703640649000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F26152758%2FDSC_1008-1.jpg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fsociety%2Freminiscences-of-father-mother-and-me%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22Mehr%C2%A0Afshan%20Farooqi%20remembers%20the%20life%2C%20work%20and%20last%20days%20of%20her%20father%2C%20Shamsur%20Rahman%20Faruqi.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A63%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fsociety%2Freminiscences-of-father-mother-and-me%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22'Settlers%20armed%20with%20long%20rifles%2C%20guns%2C%20knives%20and%20machetes%20came'%3A%20West%20Bank%20Palestinian%20family%20driven%20from%20their%20home%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%22%2C%22published%22%3A1703634360000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fe3.365dm.com%2F23%2F12%2F768x432%2Fskynews-west-bank-johnston_6404857.jpg%3F20231226234348%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews.sky.com%2Fstory%2Fsettlers-armed-with-long-rifles-guns-knives-and-machetes-came-west-bank-pale